    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "That makes sense. I saw a note in the manual about blockages being caused by tiny things like insects or even ice buildup. What exactly happens to the airspeed indicator if the tube gets clogged while the plane is in flight? Like, does it just freeze at one speed or does it act erratic?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "If the pitot tube gets clogged in flight, the airspeed indicator will generally display an incorrect, usually lower, airspeed because it is not receiving the necessary dynamic pressure. It won't necessarily \"freeze\" unless the blockage is absolute and the system is designed to default, but it will certainly read inaccurately. This error can make the pilot believe they are flying slower than they actually are, which is a serious hazard. Pilots are trained to recognize this discrepancy and switch to backup instruments or follow emergency procedures immediately.",
      "source": "target",
